<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Anchor question</div>
  Can you meet your daily needs here on foot?
</div>

<div class="stub-note">
  <strong>Fully built.</strong> All ten blocks are deep, the Sustainable Neighborhood Plan handout is complete with its rubric and standards (aligned to the updated unit plan), and both AI partners have full specs. A few specifics are still being finalized and appear as placeholders: the exact Chennai areas and their data cards, and the Land Allocation Optimizer simulator (in development). The public artifact is shared through a student takeover of the school's Instagram account for this unit. Scheduling is left date-free on purpose while Earth Week timing is confirmed.
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <p>Unit 6 widens the lens one more time. In <a href="/units/unit-5/">Unit 5</a> you weighed competing claims over water. Here you weigh competing claims over the built environment people actually live in. The frame is the <strong>15-minute neighborhood</strong>: a place where daily needs (live, work, shop, learn, heal, play, move) sit within a short walk or cycle of home, so the car becomes optional rather than mandatory.</p>
  <p>Each of you takes a <strong>Chennai area</strong> (a ward, a named neighborhood, or a defined 15-minute catchment) and redesigns it across 8 urban land uses. The catch is the one this whole year has been building toward: there is no allocation that wins on every objective. Density buys housing but costs green space. Permeable land buys flood resilience but costs buildable area. The summative, the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighborhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighborhood Plan</a>, is scored on whether you <strong>name and quantify those trade-offs honestly</strong>. A plan that claims to maximize everything is hiding its trade-offs, and that is a hard cap on the Thinking and Transfer strand.</p>
  <p>Two AI partners enter the unit and they disagree on purpose. The <strong>Urban Planner</strong> pushes density, housing, and economic vitality. The <strong>Equity &amp; Resilience Partner</strong> pushes green-blue space, flood and heat protection, and the rights of people who could be displaced. Your job is to synthesize their disagreement, not to average them or pick one.</p>
  <p>The Communication performance is public. Rather than a peer panel, you present your redesign as a real activity at the school's environmental showcase, with a shareable artifact posted through a student takeover of the school's Instagram account, framed for a real municipal audience (the Greater Chennai Corporation, the CMDA, or your ward office). The design guardrail: a public message rewards a clean story, but your artifact still has to show what your plan gave up, not hide it.</p>
</div>

